description:
This guideline is a recommendation of the BfR Committee for Exposure Assessment and Exposure Standardisation concerning the procedure of the BfR for the recording, description and assessment of uncertainties in connection with health opinions.&nbsp; 
The main purpose of uncertainty analyses is to increase transparency regarding all elements of a risk assessment/exposure assessment and to permit appropriate decisions even when there is uncertainty. &nbsp; 
For the purpose of uncertainty analysis, it is advisable to use a multi-stage procedure comprising uncertainty factors (1st stage), qualitative uncertainty analysis (2nd stage) and quantitative uncertainty analysis (3rd stage). This multi-stage procedure should, where possible, accompany the entire process of exposure assessment, a process that looks not only at the scenario but also the mathematical model and the parameters, and also covers the uncertainty of the question definition, the calculation and the model documentation. In the case of the latter, uncertainty analysis is generally confined to the qualitative stage. &nbsp; 
Qualitative uncertainty analysis aims to create a systematic procedure for the verbal description of uncertainties. This guideline provides assistance in the form of pre-defined question lists. &nbsp; 
The communication of uncertainty is an integral part of the communication of a risk assessment. In particular, it addresses the questions of who might be affected by the uncertainties, how serious the effects on the uncertainties might be, and which options for action exist.

